\pard\f0\fs28    {\b 3. C. aequitriloba} (Viv.) A. Cheval., {\i op. cit.} 646 (1937) ({\i Linaria aequitriloba} (Viv.) Sprengel). Pubescent to villous. Stems up to 40 cm; middle and upper internodes usually about equal. Leaves up to 28 × 35 mm, but often very much smaller, mostly alternate but sometimes a few opposite, orbicular to reniform, entire to 3(-5)-lobed; lobes usually low and rounded, the central not much larger than the adjacent ones. Pedicel at anthesis longer than the subtending petiole. Calyx c. 2·5 mm. Corolla 8-13 mm; spur 2-3 mm. Capsule glabrous, slightly exceeding calyx. Seeds globose, alveolate. {\i Damp or shady places. • Islands of W. Mediterranean, eastwards to Giglio.} Bl Co It Sa.
\par

\par

\pard\f0\fs28  ({\b a}) Subsp. {\b aequitriloba}: Stems slender, not fragile; leaves not fleshy; calyx hairy to subglabrous; corolla violet; seeds 0·9-1·2 mm, rather coarsely alveolate. 2n = 56.{\i  Throughout the range of the species}.
\par

\pard\f0\fs28    ({\b b}) Subsp. {\b fragilis} (Rodr.) D. A. Webb,{\i  Bot. Jour. Linn. Soc.}{\b  65}: 265 (1912) ({\i Linaria fragilis} Rodr.): stems relatively stout, fragile; leaves rather fleshy; calyx hairy; corolla pale blue to whitish; seeds 0·8-1 mm, finely alveolate.{\i  Menorca} ({\i Barrancos de Algedar, S. of Ferrerias}).
\par

