\pard\f0\fs28    {\b 5. C. pallida} (Ten.) Wettst. in Engler & Prantl,{\i  Natürl. Pflanzenfam.}{\b  4}({\b 3b}): 58 (1891). Stems and leaves usually puberulent to pubescent; more rarely (var. {\i beguinotii} (Cuf.) Cuf.) glabrous. Stems up to 20 cm; middle internodes very long, the upper much shorter, so that the long-petiolate leaves overtop the stem-apex. Leaves up to 25 × 30 mm, mostly opposite, suborbicular to semicircular-deltate, entire to 5-lobed with low and rounded to subacute, deltate lobes, the central usually much the largest. Calyx 3-4 mm, densely puberulent. Corolla 15-25(-30) mm, pale lilac-blue; spur 6-9 mm. Capsule glabrous, slightly exceeding calyx. Seeds c. 1 mm, ovoid, with acute, longitudinal ridges.{\i  Rocks and screes. • Mountains of C. Italy.} It [Br Cz].
\par

\par

\pard\f0\fs28    {\b 6. C. hepaticifolia} (Poiret) Wettst.,{\i  loc. cit.} (1891) ({\i Linaria hepaticifolia }(Poiret) Steudel). Like {\b 5} but glabrous (except sometimes for sparsely hairy calyx); some of the leaves usually alternate; calyx 4-5 mm; corolla 15-18 mm, with spur 4-5 mm; capsule slightly shorter than calyx. 2n = 56.{\i  Shady places and on rocks by streams. • Corse. }Co.
